UID:oxford-accelerator-fellowship-ethics-in-ai-2026-27@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:Deadline: Oxford Institute for Ethics in AI: Accelerator Fellowship
  Programme 2026/27
DESCRIPTION:Accelerator Fellowship Programme at the University of Oxford's 
 Institute for Ethics in AI\, supporting impact-driven projects addressing 
 the urgent ethical challenges posed by artificial intelligence\, grounded 
 in philosophical inquiry\, academic independence and a collaborative ethos
 . 3-4 fellows recruited for the 2026/27 cohort. NOT FOR: early-stage\, pro
 of-of-concept\, or blue-skies-only proposals. PROJECTS MUST: be already on
  a clear path to creating meaningful impact\, with established or clearly 
 identified partnerships\, a well-defined delivery roadmap\, and clear indi
 cators of how impact will be achieved and measured. POTENTIAL IMPACT INCLU
 DES: policy or governance innovation in AI\; new professional-development 
 opportunities in the AI industry\; commercial or technical innovation in r
 esponsible AI\; strategic networks/alliances\; transformation of public di
 scourse on AI ethics. ELIGIBILITY: practising professionals and academics 
 from any discipline\, holding a continuing role within a university\, not-
 for-profit research organisation\, industry\, or who are otherwise profess
 ionally established and engaging with AI. Open worldwide\; proficiency in 
 English required. PhD applicants: 2+ peer-reviewed publications and a risi
 ng trajectory of research including at least one grant as PI or Co-I. Non-
 PhD applicants: 7+ years equivalent professional standing with advanced ex
 pertise\, original contributions\, peer/professional recognition\, and sig
 nificant impact. WHAT FELLOWS GET: GBP 2\,000/month stipend\; economy UK t
 ravel and visa costs covered\; intellectual engagement with Oxford researc
 hers\; visibility through seminars\, public discussions\, collaborative ev
 ents\; flexible self-directed structure (no formal supervision)\; inductio
 n meeting plus a one-day retreat. FORMAT: remote with short visits\, or up
  to 6 months in-person in Oxford (subject to UK immigration eligibility)\;
  in-person stays should align with university term dates. NOTE: this is NO
 T an employed position with the University. APPLY: (1) complete the online
  application form\; (2) email the three documents (Project Statement max 5
 00 words including impact pathways and any project-cost proposal\; Motivat
 ion Letter max 500 words\; CV max 2 pages) as PDFs to aiethicsafp@philosop
 hy.ox.ac.uk with subject line 'AFP Fellowship Application' and the naming 
 convention 'Surname_Name_Month_Year_AFP_filetype'. TIMELINE: applications 
 opened 25 May 2026\; deadline 15 June 2026 23:59 UK time (programme reserv
 es the right to close applications early). VISA: if needed\, allow 6 month
 s before intended visit\; 3 months otherwise.\n\nOrganisation: Institute f
 or Ethics in AI\, University of Oxford\nLocation: Remote with intermittent
  short visits to Oxford\, OR up to 6 months in-person in Oxford\, UK\nAwar
 d: Monthly stipend of GBP 2\,000 to support accommodation\, travel\, food 
 and living expenses. Economy airfare to and from the UK and any visa costs
  covered. Project-related costs (workshops\, seminars\, public exhibitions
 /events) considered case-by-case if a clear proposal and brief cost justif
 ication are included in the application. No application fee.\nDuration: 6 
 or 12 months. Earliest remote start: September 2026. In-person start dates
 : April 2027 or September 2027\n\nMore: https://afp.oxford-aiethics.ox.ac.
 uk/join
URL:https://afp.oxford-aiethics.ox.ac.uk/join
LOCATION:Remote with intermittent short visits to Oxford\, OR up to 6 month
 s in-person in Oxford\, UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:futures-photography-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260622
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260623
SUMMARY:Deadline: FUTURES Photography: 2027 Residency Open Call
DESCRIPTION:ELIGIBILITY: Open exclusively to current FUTURES artists (exist
 ing members of the FUTURES Photography platform)\; the application is free
  of charge. CONCEPT: The residency supports emerging photographers with ti
 me\, space\, and resources to develop new work\, with a strong emphasis on
  research and artistic process. Artists are invited to explore the interse
 ction of Nature\, Environment\, and Technology - projects should challenge
  perceptions of human and ecological relationships\, technological advance
 ment\, and environmental responsibility. An interdisciplinary approach is 
 encouraged\, and each residency culminates in a public event where artists
  share their work and engage with diverse audiences. LOCATIONS: Three part
 ner venues host residencies at different times in 2027. (1) Futures Hub\, 
 Amsterdam (global FUTURES HQ): a 60 sqm ground-floor studio with heating\,
  electricity\, and private entrance\; live-work space with double folding 
 bed\, private bathroom\, washing machine\, and small kitchen\; sliding doo
 r separates work and living areas\; access to a shared atrium for large-sc
 ale works\, performances\, and presentations\; communal rooftop terrace\; 
 bed linens and towels provided\; available January\, February\, April\, Ma
 y\, June\, September\, October\, November\, December 2027. (2) ISSP\, Riga
 : private bedroom with working space in a shared city-centre apartment wit
 h two other artists\; spacious shared living room and fully equipped kitch
 en\; access to ISSP office facilities including printer\, scanner\, ISSP p
 hotography library\, and studio lights\; available May 2027. (3) Capa Cent
 er\, Budapest: fully furnished private room in a communal apartment at Art
  Quarter Budapest\; 400 sqm shared studio in a postindustrial area\; servi
 ces to integrate residents into the local Budapest art scene and establish
  professional connections\; option to organise a presentation at Capa Cent
 re in downtown Budapest\; access to Capa Centre office facilities (printer
 \, scanner)\; available April 2027. PRESENCE: minimum 90% presence require
 d throughout the residency period. ENGAGEMENT: residents contribute to a V
 isual Diary (one Instagram carousel and two Stories\, in collaboration wit
 h FUTURES)\, a short Video Portrait documenting their process\, a public e
 vent such as an open studio or workshop (open studios on the last Wednesda
 y of the month)\, and a written interview with a local writer published on
  the FUTURES website. FINANCIAL SUPPORT: EUR 1\,000 stipend to cover livin
 g expenses\, materials\, and travel\; accommodation is provided at all loc
 ations. Residents are responsible for arranging travel documents\, health 
 and travel insurance\, liability insurance\, and any visa requirements (su
 pport provided where needed). APPLY: via the FUTURES website\; application
  is free and open only to FUTURES artists. TIMELINE: deadline 22 June 2026
  at 23:59 Amsterdam time\; results announced July 2026. Contact info@futur
 es-photography.com for questions.\n\nOrganisation: FUTURES Photography\nLo
 cation: Futures Hub\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands\; ISSP\, Riga\, Latvia\; Cap
 a Center\, Budapest\, Hungary\nAward: EUR 1\,000 stipend\; accommodation p
 rovided. No application fee.\nDuration: Minimum 1 month\; location-specifi
 c dates in 2027 (Amsterdam: Jan\, Feb\, Apr\, May\, Jun\, Sep\, Oct\, Nov\
 , Dec\; Riga: May\; Budapest: Apr)\n\nMore: https://www.futures-photograph
 y.com/news/futures-residency-open-call-2027
URL:https://www.futures-photography.com/news/futures-residency-open-call-20
 27
LOCATION:Futures Hub\, Amsterdam\, Netherlands\; ISSP\, Riga\, Latvia\; Cap
 a Center\, Budapest\, Hungary
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pioneer-works-visual-arts-music-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: Pioneer Works: 2027 Open Call – Visual Arts and Music R
 esidency (Brooklyn\, NY)
DESCRIPTION:Pioneer Works in Red Hook\, Brooklyn invites applications from 
 emerging visual artists and musicians for its 2027 residency cohort. 12 Vi
 sual Arts residents (5-month residency) and 12 Music residents (1-month re
 sidency) are selected each year through a two-phase jury process. WHAT IS 
 PROVIDED: free studio space\; access to facilities including risograph pri
 nter\, darkroom\, ceramics studio\, large-format printer\, 3D printers\, t
 hermobinder\, and laser cutter\; biweekly studio visits with curators\, ga
 llerists\, critics\, and artists\; free access to all public programmes at
  Pioneer Works\, including Second Sundays (monthly open studios and perfor
 mances). FINANCIAL AWARD: USD 5\,000 for Visual Arts residents\; USD 3\,00
 0 for Music residents (each comprising a USD 2\,500 honorarium plus USD 50
 0/month for the residency duration)\; applicants' choice on how to spend i
 t. Pioneer Works does not provide housing\, travel\, or visa sponsorship. 
 ELIGIBILITY: open locally\, nationally\, and internationally\; collectives
  may apply (resources shared)\; current students and programme alumni are 
 not eligible. REVIEW PROCESS: phase one is internal scoring on technical a
 bility\, uniqueness of vision\, and future potential (nontraditional caree
 r paths given special consideration)\; highest scorers advance to an exter
 nal jury of art professionals and alumni who assess diversity of demograph
 ics and media\, genuine studio need\, and fit with Pioneer Works' public-f
 acing culture. Jury convenes September 2026\; all applicants notified by l
 ate September. Supported by Dalio Philanthropies\, the Andy Warhol Foundat
 ion\, NYC Department of Cultural Affairs\, New York State Council on the A
 rts\, and the National Endowment for the Arts. APPLY: via Pioneer Works we
 bsite by 13 July 2026. Questions: residency@pioneerworks.org.\n\nOrganisat
 ion: Pioneer Works\nLocation: Pioneer Works\, Red Hook\, Brooklyn\, New Yo
 rk\, USA\nAward: Visual Arts: USD 5\,000 one-time award (USD 2\,500 honora
 rium + USD 500/month stipend for 5 months). Music: USD 3\,000 one-time awa
 rd (USD 2\,500 honorarium + USD 500/month stipend for 1 month). Free studi
 o space and facilities access. No housing or travel provided. No applicati
 on fee.\nDuration: Visual Arts: 5 months. Music: 1 month. Cohort begins af
 ter jury decisions in late September 2026.\n\nMore: https://pioneerworks.o
 rg/residency
URL:https://pioneerworks.org/residency
LOCATION:Pioneer Works\, Red Hook\, Brooklyn\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cooper-prize-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260619
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260620
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Cooper Prize 2026 (16th Street Foundation and Company
  16\, Melbourne)
DESCRIPTION:The Cooper Prize 2026 is an international playwriting prize adm
 inistered by 16th Street Foundation and Company 16 in Melbourne\, Australi
 a. AUD 20\,000 is awarded to the winning playwright\, plus consideration f
 or a full commission and professional production. All finalists receive pr
 ofessionally directed public readings by professional actors. Open interna
 tionally to published and unpublished playwrights at any career stage with
  no geographic restrictions. Submissions must respond to thematic prompts 
 drawn from Victor Frankl's 'Man's Search for Meaning' and Dostoevsky's 'Th
 e Brothers Karamazov'\, exploring themes including doubt versus faith\, th
 e meaning of suffering\, and the power of truth. Application requires: (1)
  a one-page document covering motivation for writing\, issues to explore\,
  philosophical perspective or worldview\, and a synopsis or treatment\; (2
 ) ten pages of the play manuscript. Judging panel led by Iain Sinclair and
  Harry Haynes. Deadline: 19 June 2026. Apply via JotForm at https://form.j
 otform.com/260408855140858.\n\nOrganisation: 16th Street Foundation and Co
 mpany 16\nLocation: Melbourne\, Australia (international eligibility)\nAwa
 rd: AUD 20\,000 prize to winner\, plus consideration for a full commission
  and production of the winning work. All finalists receive professionally 
 directed public readings by professional actors. No application fee.\nDura
 tion: Prize (one-time award)\; winning work may proceed to full commission
  and production.\n\nMore: https://form.jotform.com/260408855140858
URL:https://form.jotform.com/260408855140858
LOCATION:Melbourne\, Australia (international eligibility)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rotlicht-festival-analog-photography-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: ROTLICHT Festival for Analog Photography 2026: Open Call 
 (Vienna\, Austria)
DESCRIPTION:ROTLICHT Festival for Analog Photography 2026\, organised by Zi
 gutamve – Association for Contemporary Photography\, selects 20 projects
  for exhibition at the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna. Theme: 'Anthropocene: 
 Hybrid Realities' – exploring the tension between human ecological domin
 ance and environmental fragility. Each selected winner receives: exhibitio
 n in a 1\,300+ m² venue\, publication in the official festival catalogue 
 (2 copies)\, EUR 250 cash award\, EUR 150 travel allowance\, festival pass
 \, and free registration for Photodays Rovinj 2027. Grand Prix winner addi
 tionally receives a solo exhibition\, an extra EUR 250\, a free hotel stay
 \, and a catalogue cover feature. ELIGIBILITY: open to any individual aged
  16 or older\, at any career stage\, internationally\; submissions must in
 clude at least one analog photographic process\; works must have been take
 n within the last 5 years (2021-2026)\; no AI-generated or AI-enhanced wor
 k (unless deliberately thematic). Files must be JPEG\, max 5 MB\, minimum 
 2000px on longest side\, 300 dpi. Jury selects winners by late July 2026. 
 Deadline: 30 June 2026. NOTE: EUR 20 submission fee per project applies. A
 pply at https://www.rotlicht-festival.at/open-call-submission/.\n\nOrganis
