BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wsw-artists-book-residency-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261115
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261116
SUMMARY:Deadline: WSW Artist's Book Residency Grant
DESCRIPTION:Women's Studio Workshop (WSW) offers an eight- to ten-week resi
 dency for artists to produce a limited-edition artist's book. Working inte
 nsively in WSW's studios in Rosendale\, NY\, selected artists print and bi
 nd their own books\; edition size must be between 50 and 100 copies. AMOUN
 T: $350/week stipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel
  within the Continental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. WSW
  provides technical advice\, training on new equipment\, techniques\, and 
 materials\, and production assistance. SALES CONTRACT: 20% of the edition 
 goes to the artist\; 20% (at least nine copies) stays with WSW for archiva
 l and institutional sales\; 60% goes to general distribution and sale. If 
 the artist sells through WSW\, WSW takes a 30% commission plus 20% for mar
 keting\; the artist receives a 50% commission\, paid annually around 30 Ju
 ne. WSW holds the right to sell distribution copies at a 20% discount to s
 tanding-order and repository institutions. WSW's books are held in over 45
 0 collections worldwide\, including the Library of Congress\, Yale Univers
 ity\, and Vassar College. An outside jury of artists and curators selects 
 recipients. INDIGENOUS ARTISTS: applicants may check the appropriate box o
 n the Submittable form to be considered for the BIMA Artist's Book Residen
 cy Grant for Indigenous Artists. APPLICATION MATERIALS (upload via Submitt
 able): current resume\; brief project description including media required
  (200-word maximum)\; materials budget form (Google Sheets\, Excel\, or PD
 F)\; up to ten images of recent work\; image script (title\, medium\, dime
 nsions\, date). MAILED MATERIALS (to WSW at the address below): a physical
  book mock-up demonstrating how the book will be bound or function\, actua
 l size\, with at least 1-2 fully realised spreads\; and the shipping form 
 (download and open the PDF locally). Mail to: Artist's Book Application\, 
 Women's Studio Workshop\, PO Box 489\, Rosendale\, NY 12472. Applications 
 open 1 August 2026\; deadline 15 November 2026\, 11:59pm EST\; notificatio
 n March 2027\; residency runs September through June\, one year after appl
 ication. Apply via Submittable at https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artis
 ts-book-residency-grant/.\n\nOrganisation: Women's Studio Workshop (WSW)\n
 Location: Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.\nAward: $350/week st
 ipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel within the Con
 tinental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. No application fee
 .\nDuration: 8-10 weeks\; residency runs September through June\, one year
  after application.\n\nMore: https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-bo
 ok-residency-grant/
URL:https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-book-residency-grant/
LOCATION:Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ngc-mclennan-canadian-war-art-research-fellowship-2026@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260626
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260627
SUMMARY:Deadline: Rodger and Joann McLennan Canadian War Art Research Fello
 wship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The National Gallery of Canada's Rodger and Joann McLennan Cana
 dian War Art Research Fellowship encourages and supports advanced research
  in Canadian and Indigenous Canadian war and military art. Research must r
 elate to any aspect of Canadian war or military art (including painting\, 
 drawing\, sculpture\, photography\, printmaking\, and other media) and mus
 t emphasise the use and investigation of the collections of the National G
 allery of Canada\, the Canadian War Museum\, and Library and Archives Cana
 da. The Fellowship supports original research by scholars undertaking publ
 ishing\, exhibition\, thesis\, and dissertation work or their equivalents.
  AMOUNT: up to $5\,000\, including expenses and/or stipend. TENURE: one ca
 lendar year beginning 1 September 2026\; tenable only at the National Gall
 ery of Canada. ELIGIBILITY: open to art historians\, curators\, critics\, 
 conservators\, graduate students\, and independent or other professionals 
 working in the visual arts\, museology\, and related disciplines in the hu
 manities and social sciences\; international applicants welcome. Researche
 rs from outside Canada must ensure all visa requirements and documentation
  are in order before entry and the start of the Fellowship. Applications a
 re invited from all qualified candidates\, including Indigenous peoples\, 
 women\, people of any sexual orientation\, gender identity or gender expre
 ssion\, racialized people\, and people with disabilities. TO APPLY: submit
  a complete application in English or French as a single PDF by email to A
 my Rose\, Senior Manager\, Library\, Archives and Research Fellowship Prog
 ram\, at erefel@gallery.ca. Deadline: 26 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Natio
 nal Gallery of Canada\nLocation: Ottawa\, Canada\; tenable only at the Nat
 ional Gallery of Canada.\nAward: Up to $5\,000 (including expenses and/or 
 stipend). No application fee.\nDuration: One calendar year\, beginning 1 S
 eptember 2026.\n\nMore: https://www.gallery.ca/research/fellowships/rodger
 -and-joann-mclennan-canadian-war-art-fellowship
URL:https://www.gallery.ca/research/fellowships/rodger-and-joann-mclennan-c
 anadian-war-art-fellowship
LOCATION:Ottawa\, Canada\; tenable only at the National Gallery of Canada.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-uk-winter-fellowship-2027-research-track@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI UK Winter Fellowship 2027 - Research Track
DESCRIPTION:GovAI's UK Winter Fellowship (Research Track) is a three-month 
 in-person fellowship in London for researchers and policy professionals se
 eking to enter or advance careers in AI governance and policy. Fellows con
 duct independent research on a topic of their choice\, paired with a GovAI
  supervisor from the team or network\; the first two weeks are spent explo
 ring the AI governance landscape before a research proposal is finalised. 
 Research outputs may include a report\, white paper\, journal article\, op
 -ed\, or blog post targeted at an audience relevant to AI governance. Alon
 gside the project\, fellows attend expert Q&As\, weekly seminars\, skills 
 workshops\, work-in-progress meetings\, and social events\, and are encour
 aged to discuss follow-on career opportunities with GovAI's team and netwo
 rk. GovAI alumni have gone on to roles in US\, UK\, and EU government\; le
 ading AI companies (Anthropic\, DeepMind\, OpenAI)\; top think tanks (CSET
 \, RAND)\; and leading universities (Oxford\, Cambridge). AMOUNT: £12\,00
 0 salary for three months\, plus travel support to London and weekday lunc
 h. Visa sponsorship for a 3-month temporary work visa is available\; succe
 ssful visa applicants must remain in their country of application while th
 e visa is processed. ELIGIBILITY: open to a wide range of backgrounds (gov
 ernment\, academia\, industry\, civil society)\; no strict degree requirem
 ents\; relevant areas include public policy\, political science\, computer
  science\, economics\, biosecurity\, cybersecurity\, China studies\, and r
 isk management. Senior candidates who need accommodations should email fel
 lowships@governance.ai with subject line 'senior candidate winter fellowsh
 ip 2027' and a CV. SELECTION CRITERIA: quality and clarity of written work
 \, relevant expertise\, judgement in prioritising research directions\, an
 d team fit (intellectual honesty\, openness to feedback\, comfort with unc
 ertainty). APPLICATION PROCESS: (1) written application and automated abst
 ract reasoning assessment\; (2) paid remote work test (August 2026)\; (3) 
 remote interview and reference checks (September 2026)\; decisions communi
 cated October 2026. Deadline: 12 July 2026\, 23:59 BST.\n\nOrganisation: C
 entre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: London\, UK\; in-person\
 , full-time.\nAward: £12\,000 salary for the three-month term\, plus trav
 el support to London and weekday lunch provided. Visa sponsorship (3-month
  temporary work visa) available. No application fee.\nDuration: 3 months\,
  18 January to 9 April 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.governance.ai/post/winte
 r-fellowship-2027-research-track
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/winter-fellowship-2027-research-track
LOCATION:London\, UK\; in-person\, full-time.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:anthropic-claude-corps-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260717
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260718
SUMMARY:Deadline: Claude Corps Fellowship
DESCRIPTION:Claude Corps is a national fellowship program from Anthropic pl
 acing early-career fellows full-time at nonprofits across America for one 
 year\, with the goal of extending AI's benefits to communities and buildin
 g fellows' AI skills. Anthropic funds the program and provides Claude expe
 rtise\; CodePath (America's largest collegiate CS education provider) is t
 he fellows' official employer of record and leads programming\; Social Fin
 ance leads measurement and evaluation. AMOUNT: $85\,000 full-time salary p
 lus benefits\; expansive Claude token budget\; relocation support as neede
 d. FELLOW EXPERIENCE: intensive Claude training at the start\; five hours 
 of ongoing weekly training throughout\; support from a CodePath mentor\; A
 nthropic office hours for technical questions\; and professional guidance 
 from the host organization manager. SAMPLE HOST ORGANIZATIONS: Braven (Chi
 cago)\, Code the Dream (Durham NC)\, Heartland Forward (Bentonville AR)\, 
 Montgomery County Food Bank (Conroe TX)\, Reef Environmental Education Fou
 ndation (Key Largo FL)\, StriveTogether (Cincinnati)\, YMCA of Greater Cha
 rlotte\, and more than 400 nonprofits total. ELIGIBILITY: anyone over 18 w
 ith under two years of full-time work experience\, regardless of education
 al background\; must be authorized to work in the US\; must be comfortable
  working with Claude and willing to relocate if necessary. COHORTS: Cohort
  1 (100 fellows\, starts October 2026) -- applications close 17 July 2026\
 ; Cohort 2 (starts January 2027) and Cohort 3 (starts August 2027) -- roll
 ing applications. Apply at https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-corps.\n\
 nOrganisation: Anthropic (funded)\; CodePath (employer of record)\; Social
  Finance (evaluation)\nLocation: USA\; in-person at host nonprofit organiz
 ations across America (placement location varies\; relocation support avai
 lable).\nAward: $85\,000 full-time annual salary plus benefits\, expansive
  Claude token budget\, and relocation support as needed. No application fe
 e.\nDuration: 12 months.\n\nMore: https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-co
 rps
URL:https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-corps
LOCATION:USA\; in-person at host nonprofit organizations across America (pl
 acement location varies\; relocation support available).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sound-image-2026-call-for-works-greenwich@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260619
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260620
SUMMARY:Deadline: SOUND/IMAGE 2026: "Artistic Intelligence" - Call for Work
 s
DESCRIPTION:SOUND/IMAGE 2026 is the 11th edition of the University of Green
 wich festival exploring sound and image practice\, running 5-8 November 20
 26 in London. This year's theme is "Artistic Intelligence": a critical ref
 lection on creative choice\, agency\, and authenticity in the context of a
 lgorithmic and AI-mediated art making. The festival cites reference points
  from Vera Molnár\, Pauline Oliveros\, John Cage\, Iannis Xenakis\, Ryoji
  Ikeda\, and Refik Anadol. Special consideration is given to students\, ap
 prentices\, and emerging artists\; submissions are welcome from composers\
 , filmmakers\, artists\, performers\, and architects. CATEGORIES ACCEPTED:
  sound and music works\; audiovisual works\; talks\; artist statements\; w
 orkshops and practical demonstrations\; live performances\; installations.
  THEMATIC AREAS: embodied knowledge and lived experience in aesthetic judg
 ement\; creative choice vs chance encounters\; ownership\, authenticity\, 
 and AI co-creation\; human and algorithmic capability\; spatial and immers
 ive audio-visual forms\; interdisciplinary practice (CreaTech)\; practice 
 research. SUBMISSION RULES: works under 15 minutes in duration (installati
 ons exempt from duration limit)\; maximum three submissions per artist acr
 oss all categories\; artists must attend and present in person\; submit se
 parately for each submission via Microsoft CMT. FESTIVAL PASS: all accepte
 d artists must purchase a festival pass at a reduced rate of £25. Notific
 ations before end of July 2026. Deadline: 19 June 2026\, 23:59 UTC+1 (exte
 nded from 12 June). Submit at https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-im
 age-2026-call-for-works/.\n\nOrganisation: University of Greenwich\nLocati
 on: University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance required.
 \nAward: No payment to artists. All accepted artists must purchase a festi
 val pass at a reduced rate of £25 (covers catering and technical support)
 .\nDuration: Festival runs 5-8 November 2026.\n\nMore: https://blogs.gre.a
 c.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/
URL:https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/
LOCATION:University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance requi
 red.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:revitalizing-rituals-2026-open-call@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260719
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260720
SUMMARY:Deadline: Revitalizing Rituals 2026 Open Call
DESCRIPTION:Revitalizing Rituals invites artists from all disciplines -- so
 und\, movement\, visual arts\, installation\, performance\, and transdisci
 plinary practices -- to join a research-creation journey across two landsc
 apes: Bhar Lazreg in Tunisia and the wetlands of Somogy County in Hungary.
  The project explores rituals as living forms of belonging: reconnecting c
 ommunities\, land\, memory\, food\, ecological reciprocity\, and the more-
 than-human world. Selected artists work with local communities as co-parti
 cipants in a shared inquiry into moving from extraction toward reciprocity
 . Organised by Homo Faber Alapítvány (Hungary). AMOUNT: EUR 6\,000 gross
  artist fee and production budget\; international travel and per diems cov
 ered\; on-site accommodation provided. ELIGIBILITY: minimum 5 years of act
 ive artistic practice\; portfolio reflecting interest in situated or relat
 ional work\; no formal degree required\; working language is English (loca
 l language navigation valued)\; must be available for the full residency c
 ycle including all international travel\; must be able to legally receive 
 the fee and invoice the organising partners from country of residence. Str
 ongly encourages applications from historically marginalised or underrepre
 sented voices. KEY DATES: Application Deadline 19 July 2026 (midnight) -- 
 note the open call PDF also references a 5 July date\; the officially prom
 oted deadline is 19 July\; Online Q&A 29 June 2026\, 14:00 Tunisia / 15:00
  CET (register at https://forms.gle/brnZvXvFe4JB8zL26)\; Online Conversati
 ons with shortlisted artists: mid July to mid August 2026\; Selection Resu
 lts: 31 August 2026\; Placemaking Camp: 1 week\, end of November 2026\, Hu
 ngary\; Storytellers Camp: 1 week\, March 2027\, Tunisia\; Residency Perio
 d: minimum 1 month (splittable)\, April to July 2027\; Final Presentation:
  August 2027\; Closing Event: 3 days\, winter/early spring 2028\, Hungary.
  Apply via the open call form linked at https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/up
 loads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Homo Faber Alapítvány (Homo Faber Foundation)\nLocation: Bhar Lazreg\, T
 unisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in-person residency acros
 s both sites.\nAward: EUR 6\,000 gross artist fee and production budget\; 
 international travel and per diems covered\; on-site accommodation provide
 d. No application fee.\nDuration: Multi-stage residency: Placemaking Camp 
 (1 week\, November 2026\, Hungary)\; Storytellers Camp (1 week\, March 202
 7\, Tunisia)\; Residency Period (minimum 1 month\, April-July 2027)\; publ
 ic presentation (August 2027)\; Closing Event (3 days\, winter/early sprin
 g 2028\, Hungary).\n\nMore: https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/0
 6/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf
URL:https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-
 in-the-RR-form.pdf
LOCATION:Bhar Lazreg\, Tunisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in
 -person residency across both sites.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hellmouth-magazine-volume-3-metamorphosis-2026@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260620
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260621
SUMMARY:Deadline: Hellmouth Magazine: Volume 3 "Metamorphosis" - Call for S
 ubmissions
DESCRIPTION:Hellmouth Magazine\, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit arts and culture pub
 lication based in Knoxville\, TN\, is seeking submissions for Volume 3 on 
 the theme of "Metamorphosis." The magazine publishes twice annually\, cove
 ring experimental essays\, critical art writing\, reviews\, interviews\, a
 nd visual art. HONORARIUM: $50 upon publication. CATEGORIES OPEN: Reviews 
 (exhibitions\, gallery events\, artist shows\, cultural happenings -- Sout
 heast focus but national/international exceptions welcomed\; 500-750 words
 )\; Interviews (artists living or dead\; video interviews also welcome\; o
 pen word count)\; Art Writing (academic or experimental essays on contempo
 rary or historical art -- artists\, movements\, zeitgeist\, concepts\, the
 ories\; 1\,200+ words)\; Visual Art (digital output or print\; best submit
 ted alongside an upcoming show or event). FICTION & POETRY: closed for thi
 s volume. THEME: Metamorphosis as transformative vehicle -- post-Anthropoc
 entric systems\, chimeras\, the post-human and transhuman\, cultural and p
 olitical shapeshifting\, transformation through art and literature in the 
 wake of collective trauma. All pitches should be approximately 500 words. 
 Read recent issues before submitting. Submissions due 20 June 2026. Submit
  at https://www.hellmouthmag.com/submit.\n\nOrganisation: Hellmouth Magazi
 ne\nLocation: Knoxville\, TN\, USA\; Southeast US focus for reviews\, but 
 national and international exceptions considered. Remote submissions.\nAwa
 rd: $50 honorarium upon publication. No submission fee.\nDuration: One-tim
 e publication in Volume 3.\n\nMore: https://www.hellmouthmag.com/submit
URL:https://www.hellmouthmag.com/submit
LOCATION:Knoxville\, TN\, USA\; Southeast US focus for reviews\, but nation
 al and international exceptions considered. Remote submissions.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:samstag-international-visual-arts-scholarship-2027@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Samstag International Visual Arts Scholarships - Class of
  2027
DESCRIPTION:The Samstag International Visual Arts Scholarships are annual s
 cholarships enabling Australian artists to develop their artistic capaciti
 es through a dedicated year of practice-based learning at an international
  institution of their choice. AMOUNT: AUD $75\,000 tax-exempt stipend\; in
 stitutional fees for one academic year (where applicable)\; return airfare
 s\; and travel and health insurance. ELIGIBILITY: Australian citizens or p
 ermanent residents aged 18 or over who are either (a) currently enrolled i
 n a practice-led visual arts program at an Australian institution of highe
 r education\, having successfully completed at least two years of an under
 graduate or postgraduate degree\; or (b) graduates of a practice-led visua
 l arts undergraduate or postgraduate qualification at an Australian instit
 ution of higher education (graduates of more than five years' standing are
  now eligible following 2023 guideline updates). PROCESS: applicants must 
 create an account in the online portal\, download the Samstag Microsoft Po
 werPoint template\, read the Class of 2027 Guidelines\, and complete and s
 ubmit the online application form. Accounts can be created before the dead
 line and applications saved for later submission. Prior applicants (Classe
 s of 2024\, 2025\, or 2026) can reuse the same account. Deadline: 30 June 
 2026\, midnight Australian Central Standard Time (ACST). Apply at https://
 samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply/.\n\nOrganisation: Samstag Museu
 m of Art\, University of South Australia\nLocation: Australia (applicants 
 must be Australian citizens or permanent residents)\; 12-month placement a
 t an international institution of the scholar's choice.\nAward: AUD $75\,0
 00 tax-exempt stipend\; institutional fees for one academic year of study 
 (where applicable)\; return airfares\; and travel and health insurance. No
  application fee.\nDuration: 12 months overseas at an international learni
 ng institution.\n\nMore: https://samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply
 /
URL:https://samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply/
LOCATION:Australia (applicants must be Australian citizens or permanent res
 idents)\; 12-month placement at an international institution of the schola
 r's choice.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:small-file-media-festival-2026-call-for-work@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Small File Media Festival 2026 - Call for Work
DESCRIPTION:The Small File Media Festival 2026 invites moving-image submiss
 ions under the theme "Can Small Files Save the World?" -- a call for artho
 use\, video work\, glitch aesthetics\, punk\, sci-fi\, narrative\, and doc
 umentary work made with a small-file mindset. This year the festival espec
 ially welcomes small-scale experiments with narrative and documentary. The
  festival frames Small File Ecomedia as a political and ecological interve
 ntion: small files function in regions with precarious infrastructure\, ci
 rcumvent bandwidth imperialism and surveillance\, and expose the environme
 ntal cost of mainstream online video. WHAT THEY WANT: craftily composed\, 
 elegantly performed\, and artfully minimised movies in any genre\; use of 
 obsolete technologies\, creative compression techniques\, and low-bandwidt
 h aesthetics at all stages of production is encouraged. Resources for maki
 ng small-file work at www.smallfile.ca/make. Open to artists\, activists\,
  media pirates\, rogue technologists\, and filmmakers. No payment or submi
 ssion fee stated. All submitted information used for festival programming 
 and promotion -- ensure accurate spelling\, punctuation\, and capitalisati
 on. Submissions close 1 July 2026 at midnight. Submit at https://smallfile
 .ca/submit/.\n\nOrganisation: Small File Media Society\nLocation: Canada\;
  festival screening. Open to international submissions.\nAward: No payment
  stated\; festival programming and screening. No submission fee stated.\nD
 uration: One-time festival screening.\n\nMore: https://smallfile.ca/submit
 /
URL:https://smallfile.ca/submit/
LOCATION:Canada\; festival screening. Open to international submissions.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hibrides-biennial-artistic-research-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260907
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260908
SUMMARY:Deadline: Híbrides: Small Embodied Data - Call for Contributions (
 2nd Edition)
DESCRIPTION:Híbrides is a biennial of artistic research co-organised by th
 e Axolot.cat collective and the DARTS (Design\, Art\, Technology and Socie
 ty) research group at the UOC in Barcelona. The second edition\, "Small Em
 bodied Data\," centres on the concept of classification -- approached thro
 ugh machine learning\, data science\, algorithmic systems\, and questions 
 of who designs classifiers\, under what ethical codes\, and to what end. T
 he biennial brings classification into dialogue with its previous themes o
 f Small Data (community-defined\, intentional data collection and analysis
 ) and Embodiment (bodily experience as a foundation of situated\, sensory 
 knowledge). Both academic and non-academic contributions are welcome. FORM
 ATS ACCEPTED: Oral Presentations (20 minutes\; artistic practice\, artisti
 c research\, or academic research projects\; may be video-recorded for a p
 ublic archive and developed into short papers)\; Performances (20-30 minut
 es\; must engage with the physical body\, stage\, and technology\; complet
 e works\, including previously presented work\; takes place in a multipurp
 ose space with technical support). SUBMISSION REQUIREMENTS: online form wi
 th abstract (max 1\,000 characters)\, professional biography (max 1\,000 c
 haracters)\, and link to representative materials (3-5 images\; video and 
 technical rider required for performances). HONORARIA: oral presentations 
 €100\; performances €400\; invoice required in both cases. Participant
 s must follow the event's code of conduct. Event runs 26-28 November 2026 
 at UOC Poblenou campus and Convent de Sant Agustí\, Barcelona. Deadline: 
 7 September 2026. Submit at https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.html.\n\n
 Organisation: Axolot.cat collective and DARTS research group\, Universitat
  Oberta de Catalunya (UOC)\nLocation: Barcelona\, Spain\; UOC Poblenou cam
 pus and Convent de Sant Agustí. In-person attendance required.\nAward: Or
 al presentations: €100 honorarium (invoice required). Performances: €4
 00 honorarium (invoice required). No submission fee.\nDuration: Festival r
 uns 26-28 November 2026.\n\nMore: https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.htm
 l
URL:https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.html
LOCATION:Barcelona\, Spain\; UOC Poblenou campus and Convent de Sant Agust
 í. In-person attendance required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bmi-foundation-babyface-award-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: BMI Foundation Babyface Award 2026
DESCRIPTION:The BMI Foundation Babyface Award is an inaugural annual award 
 supporting emerging songwriters working in R&B\, hip-hop\, soul\, and musi
 c of the African diaspora. Founded with a $25\,000 investment from Wells F
 argo. AMOUNT: $10\,000 career grant plus artistic and business mentorship.
  ELIGIBILITY: ages 18-29 as of 30 June 2026\; US residents or those in US 
 territories\; submitted works must be unpublished and unassigned to major 
 labels or publishers (self-released works are eligible)\; co-written works
  are eligible if all writers meet the eligibility criteria (maximum 3 writ
 ers\; award split evenly). One application per person per year\; cannot su
 bmit the same work to multiple BMI Foundation programs. No affiliation wit
 h BMI required. APPLICATION MATERIALS: a 1-2 minute personal statement vid
 eo\; two audio files with anonymized lyric sheets (lyrics may be in any la
 nguage with English translation)\; and a description of the creative proce
 ss (audio\, visual\, or written format). No application fee. Apply via Goo
 gle Form at https://bmifoundation.org/by-application/babyfaceaward. Deadli
 ne: 30 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: BMI Foundation\nLocation: USA\; remote 
 application.\nAward: $10\,000 career grant plus artistic and business ment
 orship. No application fee.\nDuration: One-time award.\n\nMore: https://bm
 ifoundation.org/by-application/babyfaceaward
URL:https://bmifoundation.org/by-application/babyfaceaward
LOCATION:USA\; remote application.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wheeler-centre-next-chapter-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Wheeler Centre: The Next Chapter 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Next Chapter is The Wheeler Centre's flagship writing progr
 am\, designed to elevate Australian stories that are underrepresented and 
 to nurture a new wave of writers to tell them. Each fellow receives a AUD 
 $15\,000 stipend and is paired with a handpicked mentor for a twelve-month
  period to progress a major writing project. Fellows also receive a reside
 ncy at Varuna\, The National Writers' House\; an end-of-year publishing in
 tensive at The Wheeler Centre\; and meaningful opportunities to connect wi
 th peers\, agents\, publishers\, and readers. One fellowship place is dedi
 cated specifically to a poet: The Malcolm Robertson Fellowship. 2027 judge
 s: Melissa Lucashenko\, Micaela Sahhar\, Cher Tan\, and Melanie Saward. EL
 IGIBILITY: Australian writers. No specific genre restrictions stated\; the
  program focuses on stories that are not currently being told and voices t
 hat are underrepresented. TIMELINE: submissions open 2 June 2026\; submiss
 ions close 31 July 2026 (5pm)\; 2027 Next Chapter Fellows announced 10 Nov
 ember 2026. Questions: thenextchapter@wheelercentre.com. Apply at https://
 www.wheelercentre.com/the-next-chapter.\n\nOrganisation: The Wheeler Centr
 e\nLocation: Melbourne\, Australia\; includes residency at Varuna\, The Na
 tional Writers' House\, and an end-of-year publishing intensive at The Whe
 eler Centre.\nAward: AUD $15\,000 stipend per fellow. No application fee.\
 nDuration: 12 months.\n\nMore: https://www.wheelercentre.com/the-next-chap
 ter
URL:https://www.wheelercentre.com/the-next-chapter
LOCATION:Melbourne\, Australia\; includes residency at Varuna\, The Nationa
 l Writers' House\, and an end-of-year publishing intensive at The Wheeler 
 Centre.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:richell-prize-emerging-writers-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Richell Prize for Emerging Writers 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Richell Prize for Emerging Writers\, presented by the Emerg
 ing Writers' Festival and Hachette Australia\, is an annual prize for unpu
 blished writers of adult fiction and adult narrative non-fiction. The winn
 er receives AUD $10\,000 and a 12-month mentorship with a Hachette Austral
 ia publisher\, who will work with the writer to develop their manuscript\,
  with first option to consider the finished work for publication. Long- an
 d short-listed writers are also eligible to apply for a Casa Morphosi Resi
 dency in Abruzzo\, Italy. The prize was established in memory of Hachette 
 Australia CEO Matt Richell (d. 2014). ELIGIBILITY: must currently reside i
 n Australia (Australian citizens\, permanent residents\, and long-term vis
 a holders residing in Australia\; those residing overseas are not eligible
 )\; unpublished writers only -- no previous publication by a publishing ho
 use (including small press or independent publishers in any genre)\; publi
 cation in anthologies\, literary journals\, scholarly works\, writing PhD 
 projects\, or self-publishing does not disqualify. ELIGIBLE GENRES: adult 
 fiction (including short story collections) and adult narrative non-fictio
 n (including memoir and essay collections). Poetry\, scripts\, plays\, pic
 ture books\, practical non-fiction\, and works for children or young adult
 s are not eligible. SUBMISSION FORMAT: single PDF comprising the first thr
 ee chapters (maximum 20\,000 words)\, a one-page synopsis\, and a chapter 
 breakdown of up to two A4 pages\; plus a statement (up to 750 words) on ho
 w winning the prize will further your writing career\, entered in the onli
 ne form. Manuscript must be complete or intended to be completed\; does no
 t need to be finished at time of submission. A4\, double-spaced\, 12pt Rom
 an font (e.g. Garamond or Times New Roman)\, 3cm margins\, page numbers. T
 IMELINE: prize opened 23 April 2026\; closes 13 July 2026 at 11:59pm AEST\
 ; longlist announced 11 September 2026\; shortlist 16 October 2026\; winne
 r announced 6 November 2026. Administered with support from Simpsons Solic
 itors. Apply at https://emergingwritersfestival.org.au/richell-prize-2026/
 .\n\nOrganisation: Emerging Writers' Festival and Hachette Australia\nLoca
 tion: Australia\; must currently reside in Australia.\nAward: AUD $10\,000
  prize money (donated by Hachette Australia)\; 12-month mentorship with a 
 Hachette Australia publisher\; first option to consider finished work for 
 publication. Long- and short-listed writers also eligible to apply for a C
 asa Morphosi Residency in Abruzzo\, Italy. No application fee.\nDuration: 
 12-month mentorship.\n\nMore: https://emergingwritersfestival.org.au/riche
 ll-prize-2026/
URL:https://emergingwritersfestival.org.au/richell-prize-2026/
LOCATION:Australia\; must currently reside in Australia.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:adk-ems-berlin-stockholm-residency-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: AdK / EMS Berlin-Stockholm Bilateral Residency Program 20
 26-27
DESCRIPTION:A new bilateral residency collaboration between the Studio für
  Elektroakustische Musik at the Akademie der Künste in Berlin and Elektro
 nmusikstudion EMS in Stockholm. Four artists will be selected to develop a
 nd present new works in both cities\, with presentations at KONTAKTE 2027 
 in Berlin and at a corresponding event in Stockholm. The program supports 
 new artistic and technical initiatives at the intersection of sound\, musi
 c\, and technology in the field of time-based\, performative\, and digital
  arts. ELIGIBLE CATEGORIES: (1) new instrumental and live-electronic works
 \; (2) acousmatic music\, computer music\, radio art\, and other forms of 
 electroacoustic music and sound art\; (3) projects from artists of any dis
 cipline for whom sound is a central element\; (4) curatorial\, publishing\
 , and educational projects in sound-based art practice\, particularly thos
 e relating in content to the AdK Studio or EMS\; (5) independent research 
 in acoustics\, computer science\, or musicology -- specifically software d
 evelopment\, spatialization\, or network technologies. Open to individuals
  and groups. Project duration is flexible and arranged by agreement. SUPPO
 RT: travel and accommodation costs for Berlin and Stockholm covered\; pres
 entation fees paid for both venues. Selection is made by the director and 
 advisory board of the Studio für Elektroakustische Musik and the director
  of EMS\; decision is final with no legal entitlement to funding. Incomple
 te or late applications are not considered. This call supplements the Stud
 io's regular residency program (separate deadline June 30\, 2026 for July-
 December 2026 period). Apply exclusively via the online form at https://nc
 .adk.de/index.php/apps/forms/s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA. Questions: estudi
 o@adk.de. Deadline: 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Studio für Elektroakus
 tische Musik\, Akademie der Künste (Berlin) and Elektronmusikstudion EMS 
 (Stockholm)\nLocation: Berlin\, Germany and Stockholm\, Sweden\; travel an
 d accommodation covered for stays in both cities.\nAward: Travel and accom
 modation costs for stays in Berlin and Stockholm covered\; fees paid for p
 resentation at KONTAKTE Festival 2027 (Berlin) and for presentation in Sto
 ckholm. Amount not publicly stated. No application fee.\nDuration: Flexibl
 e\, by agreement\; works to be presented at KONTAKTE 2027 in Berlin and at
  a Stockholm presentation.\n\nMore: https://nc.adk.de/index.php/apps/forms
 /s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA
URL:https://nc.adk.de/index.php/apps/forms/s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA
LOCATION:Berlin\, Germany and Stockholm\, Sweden\; travel and accommodation
  covered for stays in both cities.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:democracy-stories-lab-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260617T130707Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260914
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260915
SUMMARY:Deadline: Democracy Stories Lab: Open Call for Visual Storytellers
DESCRIPTION:The Democracy Stories Lab\, an initiative of People Powered (a 
 global hub for participatory democracy) in partnership with the Democracy 
 Narratives Alliance\, invites creators worldwide to submit visual content 
 -- short videos\, illustrations\, or graphics -- that tells a compelling s
 tory about democracy\, voice\, fairness\, belonging\, and community power.
  Content can be original or already published\, as long as it is the appli
 cant's own work and engages with narrative frameworks from the Democracy N
 arratives Alliance's research on 'How to Talk About Democracy.' Tone is op
 en\; serious and comedic approaches are both welcome. AWARDS: 4 winning en
 tries receive USD $1\,000 each\; 5 honorable mentions receive USD $500 eac
 h\; all winners receive amplification across People Powered and Democracy 
 Narratives Alliance communications networks and are featured in a global s
 creening event. WHO CAN APPLY: individual creators and small teams anywher
 e in the world\; especially welcomes creators who reach audiences outside 
 usual democracy circles\, who come from communities traditionally with les
 s of a say in public discourse\, and who work in civic tech\, advocacy\, c
 ommunity organising\, comedy\, art\, illustration\, games\, or lifestyle c
 ontent. Applications open 14 July 2026 via the Democracy Stories Lab page 
 at https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-sto
 ries-lab\; subscribe to the People Powered newsletter to be notified when 
 the form opens. Submission deadline: 14 September 2026. Winners announced 
 October-November 2026. Note: the initiative was itself voted into existenc
 e through People Powered's participatory budgeting process (PP Decides).\n
 \nOrganisation: People Powered and Democracy Narratives Alliance\nLocation
 : Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners.\nAward: USD $1\,
 000 for each of 4 winners\; USD $500 for each of 5 honorable mentions. Plu
 s amplification across People Powered and Democracy Narratives Alliance ne
 tworks and feature in a global screening event. No application fee.\nDurat
 ion: One-time award.\n\nMore: https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/a
 nnouncing-the-democracy-stories-lab
URL:https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-sto
 ries-lab
LOCATION:Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
